{North opens 1\S, her 5-card Major and South responds 2\H. North knows this is a 5-card suit, and bids 3\H, confirming the 8+card trump fit.

Once the trump fit is known, South revalues his hand to about 19 points. He makes a slam try with  a control-showing bid of 3\S. He knows North won't take this as \S support since the partnership has agreed that \Hs are going to be trumps.

North now shows her control by bidding 4\C.

That was what South needed to hear; when Blackwood uncovers two Aces he bids 6\H.

The slam is a good one. If either the \SQ or \CK is right there are 12 tricks by way of a finesse. But the best way to play the hand would be to try to establish a \S in the North hand, and if that fails try the \C finesse.}
